                    <physDesc>
                        <objectDesc>
                            <supportDesc>
                                <support><p><term>monument</term> <ref target="https://archwilio.org.uk/her/chi3/arch.php?lang=eng">Dyfed Archaeological Trust Historic Environment Record</ref>: <idno type="HER">3943</idno> St Gwinio's Church</p>
                                    <material type="stone">Dark grey gabbro</material> 
                                    <objectType key="monument">Pillar</objectType> <note>comprised of <q>dark grey gabbro, 20 per cent feldspar phenocrysts, 5 per cent of which are weathered, much chlorite. Weathered surface is light brown (7.5YR 6/2 - 6/4).</q> (Edwards 2007, 264).</note>
                                    <dimensions unit='m'>
                                        <height>1.14</height>
                                        <width>0.38</width>
                                        <depth>0.305</depth>
                                        </dimensions></support> 

                                <condition/>
                            </supportDesc>
                            <layoutDesc>
                                <layout style="vertical" rend="arris_up-up"><q>A roman-letter, Latin inscription is <rs type="execution" key="incised" ref="https://www.eagle-network.eu/voc/writing/lod/1.html">incised</rs>, using very broad lines, in three lines reading vertically downwards (from the original top of the monument)...</q> Two <q>...incomplete ogam inscriptions are deeply incised, using broad strokes, along the original right (A/B) and left (A/D) angles of the face, both reading upwards from the original base... The ogam inscriptions are positioned so that the corresponding words are near their roman equivalents... The short central stroke of the second V on the left side suggests that the ogam inscription was cut after and shortened so as to avoid line 3 of the roman inscription</q> (Edwards 2007, 264-267).</layout>
                            </layoutDesc>
                        </objectDesc>
                        <handDesc>
                            <handNote>The roman-letter inscription <q>...is in capitals... the letters in line 3 are smaller than the rest, owing to a lack of space. Three of the I's have triangular serifs. In line 1 VA are ligatured and the stroke of the V joins the A at the level of the crossbar; the second I is horizontal. In line 2 the A and V are rather rounded and the V is placed diagonally; the second B has separate loops. The V in line 3 is flattened and slightly rounded</q> (Edwards 2007, 264-265).
                                <height></height>
                            </handNote>
                        </handDesc>
