            <div type="translation">
                <div type="textpart" n="1">
                    <p><title>Ogham</title>: 'B<choice><unclear reason="faded">i</unclear><unclear reason="faded">e</unclear></choice>vv<gap reason="illegible" extent="unknown"></gap>... grandson (or descendant) of Boddi...'</p>
                </div>
               </div>
              <div type="textpart" n="2">
                  <p><title>Latin</title>: 'Of<foreign xml:lang="pgl">Bivadus</foreign> grandson (or descendant) of <foreign xml:lang="pgl">Bodibeve</foreign>'</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                        <p>The ogam inscription is a variant of the 'X son of Y' formula. Enough survives <q>...to demonstrate that the ogam inscriptions are broadly the same as the roman, but the forms of the names are slightly different and <hi rend="italic">avi</hi> is spelt <hi rend="italic">avvi</hi>... The names are both Irish. ...Both Llanwinio names contain the popular Insular Celtic name-element 'living (OI <hi rend="italic">béo</hi>, W. <hi rend="italic">byw</hi>. ...Probably, however, it is a preform of the attested Old Irish masculine o-stem name <hi rend="italic">Búaidbéo</hi>, in which case -E represents the Irish or Latin genitive -I... Linguistically it is not possible to choose between -BEV- and -BIV- wherever the readings are unclear, since both are possible...</q> (Edwards 2007, 264-267).</p>
                        <p><q>The roman-letter, Latin inscription uses a variant of the 'X son of Y' formula in the genitive case with <hi rend="italic">avi</hi> rather than <hi rend="italic">fili</hi>... <hi rend="italic">Avi</hi>, meaning 'grandson' or 'descendant', is a straight transliteration of the primitive Irish found in the ogam <hi rend="italic">avvi</hi>, rather than a Latin translation (Edwards 2007, 264-267; Jackson 1953, 180-181)</q>.</p>
                    </div>
